First, we need to find the symmetric difference of A and B (A △ B). The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets A or B, but not in their intersection.

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}

Intersection of A and B: {2, 3}

A △ B = {1, 4} (elements in either A or B, but not in their intersection)

Now, we have C = {3, 4, 5}. We need to find the symmetric difference of (A △ B) and C.

(A △ B) = {1, 4}
C = {3, 4, 5}

Intersection of (A △ B) and C: {4}

Symmetric difference of (A △ B) and C: {1, 3, 5} (elements in either (A △ B) or C, but not in their intersection)

So, the symmetric difference of (A △ B) ∪ C is {1, 3, 5}.
